{
  "doc_id": "57463",
  "text": "Recent data illuminate a role for cellular lipoxygenases in the pathogenesis and protection from metabolic disease. In humans, a recent large cohort adults with type 2 diabetes demonstrated a potentially protective role for 5-lipoxygenases ALOX5 and ALOX5AP against diabetes mellitus [CITATION_1] . Conversely, ALOX12/15 inhibition in rodent models inhibited oxidative stress, b-cell deterioration, hepatic steatosis and systemic inflammation [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Together, these data suggest that intracellular lipid intermediary metabolism drives both tissue-level and whole-organism metabolic homeostasis. The concept that the fasting state might modulate lipoxygenase activity as part of the broadly adaptive effects of fasting on metabolism remained heretofore unexplored.",
